But it's not 270.

00:53:04.230 --> 00:53:05.280
Good question.

00:53:05.280 --> 00:53:07.170
So I'm not going to go
through the details.

00:53:07.170 --> 00:53:10.818
But cross-border payments
have more complexity.

00:53:10.818 --> 00:53:12.610
I'm not going to go
through, but the paym--

00:53:12.610 --> 00:53:15.330
this is the what I'll
call the front end.

00:53:15.330 --> 00:53:18.570
You have a payer on the left
and a payee on the right.

00:53:18.570 --> 00:53:21.000
Think of somebody in the US
sending money to somebody

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:23.970
in the Philippines, maybe.

00:53:23.970 --> 00:53:27.990
I need on my side a
payment system processor.

00:53:27.990 --> 00:53:29.400
That's the bubble on the top.

00:53:29.400 --> 00:53:32.490
I need them to have some
payment system processor.

00:53:32.490 --> 00:53:35.250
They're both ends
on the front end.

00:53:35.250 --> 00:53:41.760
So just think more complexity,
more friction in the system.

00:53:41.760 --> 00:53:45.270
And really the reason is, is
because you're jumping from one

00:53:45.270 --> 00:53:47.033
money to another money.

00:53:47.033 --> 00:53:49.200
Or another way you can think
of it as you're usually

00:53:49.200 --> 00:53:52.950
jumping from one ledger system
to another ledger system,

00:53:52.950 --> 00:53:57.060
if you're thinking like the
computers and recording.

00:53:57.060 --> 00:54:00.570
And the back end--

00:54:00.570 --> 00:54:03.630
I should have called this back
end, but I labeled both of them

00:54:03.630 --> 00:54:05.910
front end, sorry--

00:54:05.910 --> 00:54:09.138
has a bunch of
things inside of it.

00:54:09.138 --> 00:54:10.680
And the one I'm just
going to mention

00:54:10.680 --> 00:54:13.440
is correspondent banking.

00:54:13.440 --> 00:54:18.330
It is a feature that came
out of centuries of banking.

00:54:18.330 --> 00:54:21.370
Arguably, you might not
need it as much now.

00:54:21.370 --> 00:54:25.680
But the concept was, I'm a
small regional bank in the US.

00:54:25.680 --> 00:54:30.900
I'm sending something to
somebody in the Philippines.

00:54:30.900 --> 00:54:32.880
The Philippines
doesn't recognize

00:54:32.880 --> 00:54:35.730
this small regional bank,
let's say, in Kansas.

00:54:35.730 --> 00:54:38.880
I need a correspondent
bank that they can trust.

00:54:38.880 --> 00:54:43.380
So it's a cost of trust that
it could go from one country's

00:54:43.380 --> 00:54:50.630
bank through a bank called
a correspondent bank, which

00:54:50.630 --> 00:54:53.630
had trust, to the
other country's bank.

00:54:53.630 --> 00:54:55.610
Or maybe you even had
correspondent banks

00:54:55.610 --> 00:54:56.420
in both countries.

00:54:56.420 --> 00:55:01.850
But usually you had one
international bank in between.

00:55:01.850 --> 00:55:03.480
Hugo.

00:55:03.480 --> 00:55:08.130
AUDIENCE: Hypothetically,
if there became enough trust

00:55:08.130 --> 00:55:10.200
in the Bitcoin
network, could that

00:55:10.200 --> 00:55:12.900
act as the correspondent bank?

00:55:12.900 --> 00:55:16.290
Where like you're in the US,
you go to a Chase or whatever.

00:55:16.290 --> 00:55:18.450
They transfer your US
dollars to Bitcoin.

00:55:18.450 --> 00:55:20.398
You go over to the
Philippines, they transfer

00:55:20.398 --> 00:55:21.440
your Bitcoin [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:21.440 --> 00:55:23.430
There is no need for that.

00:55:23.430 --> 00:55:25.410
GARY GENSLER: So Hugo's
asking whether Bitcoin

00:55:25.410 --> 00:55:28.650
or any cryptocurrency could play
that role of a correspondent

00:55:28.650 --> 00:55:33.580
bank, or effectively play the
bridge currency between fiat

00:55:33.580 --> 00:55:37.270
to crypto, US dollar
to Bitcoin, you said.

00:55:37.270 --> 00:55:39.210
And what was the other country?

00:55:39.210 --> 00:55:40.780
The Philippines.

00:55:40.780 --> 00:55:43.190
Which is a peso?

00:55:43.190 --> 00:55:45.070
What's that?

00:55:45.070 --> 00:55:45.570
Peso.

00:55:45.570 --> 00:55:46.080
Yeah.

00:55:46.080 --> 00:55:51.450
So US dollar fiat to crypto
Bitcoin to Philippine peso.

00:55:51.450 --> 00:55:54.720
That is called a bridge
crypto or bridge currency.

00:55:54.720 --> 00:55:59.010
That's, in fact, what Ripple
is trying to do with XRP.

00:55:59.010 --> 00:56:04.950
So Ripple is a company that
started as a payment messaging

00:56:04.950 --> 00:56:08.730
service to compete with Swift.

00:56:08.730 --> 00:56:12.270
And that messaging
service, which

00:56:12.270 --> 00:56:16.110
we'll talk about more Thursday,
has been adopted by many banks.

00:56:16.110 --> 00:56:19.410
More recently in 2018 they
rolled out a prototype

00:56:19.410 --> 00:56:22.950
of using a crypto token--

00:56:22.950 --> 00:56:26.160
XRP-- as a bridge currency.

00:56:26.160 --> 00:56:28.530
I would say yes,
that is possible.

00:56:28.530 --> 00:56:33.990
I think there's an issue
also about volatility.

00:56:33.990 --> 00:56:41.510
So if you're moving fiat
dollar to crypto Bitcoin XRP

00:56:41.510 --> 00:56:47.920
to fiat, if you have
a lot of volatility,

00:56:47.920 --> 00:56:51.630
that means it's a less--

00:56:51.630 --> 00:56:53.560
it could be costly.

00:56:53.560 --> 00:56:56.110
But if it's stable
value, so you can

00:56:56.110 --> 00:56:58.900
you can lower the
cost two ways--

00:56:58.900 --> 00:57:04.160
lowering the volatility of
the crypto or lower the time.

00:57:04.160 --> 00:57:06.770
And XRP believes they
have a solution that

00:57:06.770 --> 00:57:09.120
can be down to seconds.

00:57:09.120 --> 00:57:12.290
And thus, even if it's
volatility, that in seconds

00:57:12.290 --> 00:57:13.385
it won't move as much.

00:57:13.385 --> 00:57:14.760
And the friction
will be that you

00:57:14.760 --> 00:57:21.360
have to sell dollars to buy XRP,
and then sell XRP to buy peso.

00:57:21.360 --> 00:57:25.110
Or you can interpose
any bridge currency.

00:57:25.110 --> 00:57:28.830
One of the most significant
opportunities for stable value

00:57:28.830 --> 00:57:31.830
tokens that we'll talk about
in a few classes is maybe

00:57:31.830 --> 00:57:34.170
is what we can call it
is a bridge currency

00:57:34.170 --> 00:57:36.017
for cross-border.

00:57:36.017 --> 00:57:36.600
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:57:36.600 --> 00:57:38.960
The question is, what
will be the fees?

00:57:38.960 --> 00:57:43.120
And if it makes sense from
an economic [INAUDIBLE]..

00:57:43.120 --> 00:57:46.620
GARY GENSLER: So Western Union
